-- 3 cases in Italian numbers:
0-9: you just learn them
10-19: they’re basically all irregular, learn them: 10->16 end with -dici, 17-19: they START with dici-
20 on: base of the “decine” + number. If the base is “sessanta” (60), 61 is sessant- uno

S (as in rose) or HARD S (as in signature)?
If it’s followed by a consonant, it’s a HARD s: (Spesa, master) If it’s followed by a vowel:
- Single S: SOFT S (rosa, speSa)
- Double S: HARD S (SaSSari, Messa, speSSA)

