E / ed (= and):
- e + consonant = Hepsiba e Paolo
- E + vowel:

- “Informal way” -> e = Hepsiba e Anna
- Correct way -> ed = Hepsiba ed Anna


A. THE FIVE BIG ITALIAN OPEN QUESTIONS(NOTyes/no):

1. Chi (Who) -> “Chi sei, Hepsiba?” = “Who are you, Hepsiba?”
2. Come (How) -> “Come stai, Hepsiba?” = “How are you, Hepsiba?”
3. Dove (Where) -> “Dove sei, Hepsiba?” = “Where are you, Hepsiba?”
4. Quando (When) -> “Quando vieni, Hepsiba?” = “When are you coming, Hepsiba?”
5. Perché (Why) -> ‘Perché vieni, Hepsiba?’ = “why do you come?”
 
6. (Cosa) -> What (as in object of the sentence, not subject: “Cosa fa il sole?”)
7. (Quanto) -> How much (“Quanto costa la pizza?”)


B. CLOSED QUESTIONS (yes/no)

1. Basic form: (PERSON) + (VERB) + (complements),

If from the context the subject is clear, we can omit the person: the subject will be understood just by the implicit person indicated by the verb: “Hai una penna?”, “Hanno una penna?”
e.g. ‘TU + LAVORI + per Olga?’, ‘Francesca ama il colore giallo?’, ‘tu pensi che il governo sia bravo?’, ‘(tu) Hai una penna rossa, per favore?’
