FALSE FRIEND ALERT!
Mio cugino è mio parente ma non è un mio genitore.
-> My cousin is a relative of mine but he’s not my parent.
I miei genitori sono parenti ma non tutti i parenti sono miei genitori. -> My parents are relatives but not all relatives are my parents.
Ci -> soft c “like beach”


So, now we’ve seen:
- OPEN QUESTIONS: Chi\Dove\Come\Quando\Perché tu vai a mangiare?
- CLOSED QUESTIONS: Tu lavori? Francesca ama la pizza? I pesci nuotano? Il tuo lavoro è bello?

New type of question:
- OPEN QUESTIONS ABOUT SOMETHING “a complement”: we are talking not about
you and your tastes, or about somthing that fish as animal do, but about the object of the sentence: for instance “il tuo lavoro”

“What job are you doing?”
What job (=object complement) are (=verb pt.1) you (=subject) doing (=verb pt.2)?
           
- Subject: you
- Object complement: the job
The italian sentence is structured like that:
- Che\cosa + (object) + (verb) + {(complements)}
What do you work as? -> Che lavoro fai?
What do you work as at the pizza parlor? -> Che lavoro fai in pizzeria?

